% ── Abstract ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\clearpage
\thispagestyle{plain}
\chapter*{Abstract}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Abstract}

This capstone report investigates the decomposition of unitary operators, with a focus on decomposition algorithms, the structure of basic quantum gates, and the role of entanglement in multi-qubit operations. The work is organised in two parts.
Part~I develops the background necessary to study circuit synthesis. Chapter~1 establishes the mathematical framework (Hilbert spaces, qubits, and linear operators), the four postulates of quantum mechanics, and the core concepts of quantum information theory: pure and mixed states, density operators, entanglement and its measures, and quantum measurement. Chapter~2 covers the circuit model of quantum computation, treating circuit structure and complexity, standard gates, universality, approximation via the Solovay-Kitaev theorem, circuit identities (Z-Y decomposition, ABCABC
ABC factorisation, conjugation relations), and the Gray code argument for nn
n-qubit universality. Supporting mathematical tools---spectral decomposition, polar decomposition, and singular value decomposition---are also developed here.

Part~II surveys the optimality literature directly relevant to this work, organised as a single chapter with one section per paper. Vidal and Dawson and Vatan and Williams together provide the complete solution for two-qubit gate synthesis: any two-qubit unitary can be implemented in at most three CNOT gates, with explicit optimal circuits at each tier depending on the gate's position in the Weyl chamber, and the magic basis playing a central role throughout. Yu, Duan, and Ying establish that five two-qubit gates are both necessary and sufficient for the Toffoli gate, resolving a long-standing open question via a rank argument on entangling power. D\"{u}r, Vidal, and Cirac classify three-qubit pure states into exactly six SLOCC-inequivalent classes---the GHZ class, the W class, three biseparable classes, and the fully separable class---providing the entanglement-theoretic backdrop for three-qubit gate complexity. Ac\'{\i}n et al.\ establish the correct generalisation of the Schmidt decomposition to three-qubit systems, showing that every three-qubit pure state is characterised up to local unitary equivalence by five real parameters. M\"{o}tt\"{o}nen et al.\ introduce uniformly controlled rotations as a systematic decomposition scheme for arbitrary nn
n-qubit unitaries, achieving a CNOT count of $O(4n)O(4^n)
	O(4n)$ that is asymptotically optimal. Finally, Shirilord and Rahimi-Keshari propose the block-ZXZ decomposition as an alternative to the quantum Shannon decomposition, reducing the CNOT count for circuits of practical size and connecting the recursive structure directly to the rotation-gate identities of Part~I.

\vspace{1em}
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} quantum computation, quantum circuits, circuit decomposition, entanglement, CNOT count, two-qubit synthesis, Weyl chamber, magic basis, Toffoli gate, SLOCC equivalence, uniformly controlled rotations, block-ZXZ decomposition, Solovay-Kitaev, Z-Y decomposition, Gray code.

