\part{Foundations and Circuit Model}

% ============================================================
% CHAPTER 1 — INTRODUCTION AND FOUNDATIONS
% (consolidates former Part I: Chapters 1–5)
% ============================================================
\chapter{Foundations}
\label{ch:foundations}

\section{Quantum Computation and Quantum Information}

Quantum Computation and Quantum Information (QCQI) combines computing and physics. Traditional computing does not take into account the laws of physics. Classical computing reduces to logical manipulation of bits (0,1). The value of a bit can only be 0 or 1. This is where quantum mechanics differs. Quantum Systems can exist in what is called a superposition: they are simultaneously both 0 and 1 -- with less than 1 probability in each case. (The probabilities add up to 1 always though!). This new capability allows us to simultaneously explore many paths to a solution; a phenomenon that is called quantum parallelism. Quantum parallelism provides novel solution strategies that are impossible to achieve through classical computers.

Another novel capability of quantum computers is entanglement: non-local correlations. Entanglement is a property of composite quantum systems whereby correlations persist regardless of the amount of spatial separation of the subsystems.



\section{Scope and Organisation}

One of the primary hurdles in realizing quantum computers is applying quantum processes to quantum states. Isolating a quantum state is difficult; they are very short lived systems. On top of this, applying a qunatum process is yet more difficult. In this context, it would be ideal to minimize the more expensive parts of applying  quantum process. One way this can be done is by designing better decomposition algorithms for unitary operators (quantum gates), the operators that mathematically represent certain ideal quantum processes. The primary goal of this capstone project is to investigate quantum circuit (unitary gate) decomposition,
with particular attention to decomposition algorithms, the structure of elementary gates, and
the role of entanglement in multi-qubit operations.

Chapter~1 establishes the background: the mathematical framework, the postulates of quantum
mechanics, and the essential concepts of quantum information theory. This material is
developed precisely to the point required by the circuit synthesis questions that motivate
the work. Readers already familiar with parts of this background may treat the corresponding
sections as reference material rather than sequential reading.

Chapter~2 develops the circuit model from first principles and covers the known results from
Nielsen and Chuang~\cite{nielsen2000} (especially Chapter~4) that are needed for the
subsequent analysis: universality, approximation, circuit identities, and supporting operator
decompositions.

Part~II surveys the optimality literature. These are results from research papers---not in
Nielsen and Chuang---that are directly relevant to understanding how many CNOT gates are
required for various classes of gates, and what structures underpin those bounds.



\section{Three Models of Computation}

Quantum Computing introduces a new model of computation. Let's note how this model of computing differs: Firstly the fundamental unit of information in quantum computing is a vector, and the operations performed on this vector are restricted to Unitary Operations. Moreover, suprisingly enough, reading a state (measuring, as it is called) is non-trivial, since the very act of reading it changes the state (a phenomenon referred to as "collapse") - not something you would expect on a classical computer.

Classical and Probabilistic models of computation, though, share more with each other: the fundamental unit of information is the same (a bit); reading a value does not change it. But they too differ: for one thing classical model is deterministic, for another the state space in the probabilistic model is a probability distribution unlike in the classical model for which it is just the set \{0,1\}.

Understanding quantum computation requires situating it relative to its classical and
probabilistic counterparts. \Cref{tab:models} summarises the key distinctions.

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{Comparison of classical, probabilistic, and quantum models of computation.}
	\label{tab:models}
	\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{lXXX}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Aspect}  & \textbf{Classical} & \textbf{Probabilistic}   & \textbf{Quantum}      \\
		\midrule
		Information unit & Bit                & Bit                      & Qubit                 \\
		State space      & $\{0,1\}$          & Probability Distribution & Hilbert space $\Hcal$ \\
		Evolution        & Deterministic      & Probabilistic            & Unitary               \\
		Measurement      & Non-destructive    & Non-destructive          & Disturbing            \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

This new model of computation is completely described by linear algebra, along with the postulates of quantum mechanics. Also, when working with quantum mechanics, it is very convencient to work with what is called \textbf{dirac notation}: a notation that makes it easier to represent and reason about vectors. So, let's familiarize  ourselves (or refresh our memories) with these three: dirac notation, necessary linear algebra and postulates of quantum mechanics.

\section {Dirac Notation}
$\ket{\cdot}$ is called a ket and is used to represent a column vector.
$\bra{\cdot}$ is called a bra and is used to represent a row vector. Note how this makes the inner product (left multiplying the row with the column) look elegant: $\langle \cdot \vert \cdot \rangle$. Similarly, the outer product (left multiplying a column with a row) is represented so: $\vert \cdot \rangle \langle \cdot \vert$




% ── Mathematical Framework ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

\section{Hilbert Spaces}

\begin{definition}[Hilbert Space]
	A \emph{Hilbert space} is a complete, normed, inner product space over $\CC$. The state of an isolated
	quantum system is described by a unit vector in $\Hcal$. The dimension of $\Hcal$ equals the
	number of degrees of freedom of the system. Both finite-dimensional $\Hcal_n$ and
	infinite-dimensional $\Hcal_\infty$ arise in quantum information processing.

\end{definition}

We use a Hilbert space rather than a bare vector space because distinguishing quantum states
requires orthogonality, which in turn requires an inner product.


\subsection{Inner Product on \texorpdfstring{$\CC^n$}{Cn}}

\begin{proposition}
	The map $\braket{\varphi}{\psi} = \sum_{i=1}^n \varphi_i^* \psi_i$ is a valid inner product
	on $\CC^n$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
	\emph{Conjugate symmetry:}
	$\braket{\varphi}{\psi} = \sum\varphi_i^*\psi_i = (\sum\psi_i^*\varphi_i)^* = \braket{\psi}{\varphi}^*$.

	\emph{Linearity:} follows from linearity of summation.

	\emph{Positive-definiteness:}
	$\braket{\varphi}{\varphi} = \sum|\varphi_i|^2 \geq 0$, with equality iff all $\varphi_i = 0$.
\end{proof}




\section{Operators}

There are primarily three kinds of operators we will be dealing with: Normal Operators, Unitary Operators and Hermitian Operators.

\subsection{Normal Operators}
\begin{definition}
	An operator $N$ is \emph{normal} if $NN^\dagger = N^\dagger N$.
\end{definition}

Both Unitary and Hermitian operators are Normal operators.

\subsection{Unitary Operators}
\begin{definition}
	An operator is Unitary if it satisfies the condition $U^\dagger U = U U^\dagger = I$
\end{definition}
Unitary operators are the only permissible evolutions for closed quantum systems
(Postulate~\ref{post:evolution}). They satisfy $U^\dagger = U^{-1}$, preserve inner products,
and are reversible. They can be thought of rotations and depend only on the initial and final state, not
on any intermediate path.

\subsection{Hermitian Operators}

\begin{definition}
	An operator $A$ is \emph{Hermitian} if $A = A^\dagger$. Hermitian operators represent
	physical observables; their eigenvalues are real and their eigenvectors form a complete
	orthonormal basis.
	As an example, the Hamiltonian $H = \hbar\omega X$ is the Hermitian operator representing energy. It
	determines all dynamics of the system through the Schr\"{o}dinger equation.


\end{definition}



% ── Quantum Mechanics Principles ─────────────────────────────────────────────

\section{The Four Postulates}

Quantum mechanics is built on four postulates. They are not derived from anything more
fundamental --- they are the rules of the game, chosen because they make predictions that
agree with experiment. Each postulate answers a specific question: what \emph{is} a quantum
system, what \emph{happens} to it when you look at it, what \emph{happens} to it when you
leave it alone, and what \emph{happens} when you put two systems together.

\begin{theorem}[Postulate 1 --- State Space]
	\label{post:state}
	An isolated quantum system is described by a Hilbert space $\Hcal$. The state of the system
	at any instant is a unit vector $\ket{\psi} \in \Hcal$.
\end{theorem}

Why a Hilbert space, and why a unit vector? The Hilbert space requirement is essentially the
requirement that we can talk about superpositions and interference --- both of which require
an inner product. The unit vector requirement is essentially the requirement that
probabilities add up to $1$: as we will see in Postulate~2, the probability of any
measurement outcome is computed from the inner product of $\ket{\psi}$ with itself, so if
that inner product is not $1$, the probabilities will not either.

The dimension of $\Hcal$ is the number of distinguishable states the system can be in. For
a qubit --- a two-level system --- $\Hcal = \CC^2$, and any state is a unit vector
$\ket{\psi} = \alpha\ket{0} + \beta\ket{1}$ with $|\alpha|^2 + |\beta|^2 = 1$. This is
already different from a classical bit: the state is not just $0$ or $1$ but a continuous
combination of both, with complex coefficients carrying phase information that has physical
consequences.

\begin{theorem}[Postulate 2 --- Measurement]
	\label{post:measurement}
	Quantum measurements are described by a collection $\{M_m\}$ of operators satisfying the
	completeness relation
	\[
		\sum_m M_m^\dagger M_m = I.
	\]
	When the system is in state $\ket{\psi}$, outcome $m$ occurs with probability
	\[
		p(m) = \bra{\psi}M_m^\dagger M_m\ket{\psi},
	\]
	and the state immediately after obtaining outcome $m$ is
	\[
		\ket{\psi_m} = \frac{M_m\ket{\psi}}{\sqrt{p(m)}}.
	\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{figure}[h]
	\centering
	\[
		|\psi\rangle
		\;\xrightarrow{\text{measurement}}\;
		\begin{cases}
			m, \qquad  (\text{outcome / eigenvalue}) \\
			|\psi_m\rangle, \quad (\text{post-measurement state})
		\end{cases}
	\]
	\caption{Quantum measurement produces both a classical outcome $m$ and a corresponding post-measurement state $|\psi_m\rangle$.}
	\label{fig:measurement}
\end{figure}

This postulate encodes the central strangeness of quantum mechanics. Before measurement,
the system is in a superposition $\ket{\psi}$, carrying simultaneous information about all
possible outcomes. Measurement does not just \emph{reveal} a pre-existing value --- it
\emph{produces} an outcome non-deterministically and irreversibly changes the state. This is
called collapse. After collapse, the system is in $\ket{\psi_m}$, which is a normalised
version of $M_m\ket{\psi}$: the part of the original state that is consistent with having
obtained outcome $m$.

The completeness relation $\sum_m M_m^\dagger M_m = I$ is not an extra assumption --- it is
a requirement that the probabilities are consistent. Since the $p(m)$ must sum to $1$ for
any state $\ket{\psi}$, we need
\[
	\sum_m p(m) = \sum_m \bra{\psi}M_m^\dagger M_m\ket{\psi}
	= \bra{\psi}\!\left(\sum_m M_m^\dagger M_m\right)\!\ket{\psi} = 1
\]
for all $\ket{\psi}$. This holds if and only if $\sum_m M_m^\dagger M_m = I$, which is
exactly the completeness relation.

The most important special case is a \emph{projective measurement}, where each $M_m = P_m$
is an orthogonal projector satisfying $P_m^2 = P_m$ and $P_m P_{m'} = 0$ for $m \neq m'$.
For a qubit measured in the computational basis, $P_0 = \oket{0}{0}$ and $P_1 = \oket{1}{1}$.
Applied to $\ket{\psi} = \alpha\ket{0} + \beta\ket{1}$:
\[
	p(0) = \bra{\psi}P_0\ket{\psi}
	= (\alpha^*\bra{0}+\beta^*\bra{1})\oket{0}{0}(\alpha\ket{0}+\beta\ket{1})
	= |\alpha|^2,
\]
and the post-measurement state is $P_0\ket{\psi}/|\alpha| = \ket{0}$. So measuring in the
computational basis yields $\ket{0}$ with probability $|\alpha|^2$ and $\ket{1}$ with
probability $|\beta|^2$, and the state collapses to whichever outcome was obtained. This is
why $|\alpha|^2 + |\beta|^2 = 1$ is required: probabilities must sum to $1$.

\begin{remark}
	The relative phase between $\alpha$ and $\beta$ has no effect on the outcome probabilities
	of a computational-basis measurement --- only the moduli $|\alpha|$ and $|\beta|$ appear.
	This might suggest that phase is physically irrelevant. It is not: phase becomes observable
	whenever a state interferes with itself, which is the mechanism behind every quantum
	algorithm that outperforms its classical counterpart. Phase is invisible to a single
	measurement but indispensable to the computation that precedes it.
\end{remark}

\begin{theorem}[Postulate 3 --- Composite Systems]
	\label{post:composite}
	The state space of a composite system $AB$ is the tensor product of the component spaces:
	\[
		\Hcal_{AB} = \Hcal_A \otimes \Hcal_B.
	\]
	If system $A$ is in state $\ket{\psi_A}$ and system $B$ is in state $\ket{\psi_B}$,
	the joint state is $\ket{\psi_A} \otimes \ket{\psi_B}$, written $\ket{\psi_A}\ket{\psi_B}$.
\end{theorem}

The tensor product is what makes quantum computing exponentially powerful. Two qubits have a
joint Hilbert space of dimension $2 \times 2 = 4$, spanned by $\{\ket{00}, \ket{01},
	\ket{10}, \ket{11}\}$. A general two-qubit state is
\[
	\ket{\psi} = \alpha_{00}\ket{00} + \alpha_{01}\ket{01} + \alpha_{10}\ket{10} + \alpha_{11}\ket{11},
\]
which requires four complex amplitudes to specify. Three qubits require eight, $n$ qubits
require $2^n$. The state space grows exponentially in the number of qubits, and a quantum
computer manipulates all $2^n$ amplitudes simultaneously --- this is quantum parallelism.

Not every state in $\Hcal_A \otimes \Hcal_B$ factors as $\ket{\psi_A}\ket{\psi_B}$. The
state $(\ket{00} + \ket{11})/\sqrt{2}$ is the simplest example: there is no choice of
$\ket{\psi_A} = \alpha\ket{0} + \beta\ket{1}$ and $\ket{\psi_B} = \gamma\ket{0} +
	\delta\ket{1}$ such that
\[
	(\alpha\ket{0}+\beta\ket{1})(\gamma\ket{0}+\delta\ket{1})
	= \alpha\gamma\ket{00} + \alpha\delta\ket{01} + \beta\gamma\ket{10} + \beta\delta\ket{11}
\]
equals $(\ket{00}+\ket{11})/\sqrt{2}$, because that would require $\alpha\delta = 0$ and
$\beta\gamma = 0$ while simultaneously $\alpha\gamma = \beta\delta = 1/\sqrt{2}$, which is
a contradiction. States that cannot be written as a tensor product of individual states are
called \emph{entangled}. They are nonetheless perfectly legitimate elements of the tensor
product space --- entanglement is not a pathology but a resource.

\begin{remark}
	Entanglement has no classical analogue. Two classical bits can be correlated (both $0$ or
	both $1$), but their joint state is always a pair of individual values. Two entangled qubits
	do not have individual states at all: the system as a whole is in a definite state, but
	neither qubit alone is. Measuring one qubit instantaneously determines the outcome of
	measuring the other, regardless of the physical distance between them. This is the
	non-locality that Einstein called ``spooky action at a distance'', and it is the entanglement
	resource that gives quantum communication protocols like teleportation and superdense coding
	their power.
\end{remark}

\begin{theorem}[Postulate 4 --- Evolution]
	\label{post:evolution}
	The time evolution of a closed quantum system is governed by a unitary operator $U$:
	\[
		\ket{\psi(t)} = U(t)\ket{\psi(0)}.
	\]
	For every physically realizable closed-system evolution there exists a unitary $U$ describing
	it, and conversely every unitary describes a physically realizable evolution.
\end{theorem}

Why must evolution be unitary? Three reasons, all of which turn out to be equivalent.
First, unitarity preserves the norm: $\|U\ket{\psi}\|^2 = \bra{\psi}U^\dagger U\ket{\psi}
	= \bra{\psi}\ket{\psi} = 1$, so a unit vector stays a unit vector and probabilities remain
consistent. Second, unitarity is equivalent to reversibility: $U^\dagger = U^{-1}$, so the
evolution can always be undone by applying $U^\dagger$. Third, the Schrödinger equation
$i\hbar\,d\ket{\psi}/dt = H\ket{\psi}$ (where $H$ is the Hermitian Hamiltonian) has
solutions $\ket{\psi(t)} = e^{-iHt/\hbar}\ket{\psi(0)}$, and $e^{-iHt/\hbar}$ is always
unitary when $H$ is Hermitian.

We can verify unitarity explicitly for the simplest non-trivial case. The Pauli $X$ gate,
which flips $\ket{0} \leftrightarrow \ket{1}$, has matrix $X = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\1&0
	\end{pmatrix}$. Then
\[
	X^\dagger X
	= \begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}
	= \begin{pmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{pmatrix} = I,
\]
confirming $X$ is unitary. The same calculation works for $Y$, $Z$, $H$, and every other
quantum gate: they are all unitary by construction.

\begin{remark}
	The contrast between Postulates~\ref{post:measurement} and~\ref{post:evolution} is the
	central tension of quantum mechanics. When a system evolves freely (Postulate~4), the
	evolution is deterministic, linear, and reversible. When it is measured
	(Postulate~\ref{post:measurement}), the outcome is probabilistic, nonlinear (the normalisation
	step $M_m\ket{\psi}/\sqrt{p(m)}$ is not a linear map), and irreversible. A quantum computation
	exploits both: unitary gates manipulate the amplitudes deterministically to make the desired
	answer probable, and then measurement extracts the answer. The art of quantum algorithm
	design is arranging the unitary part so that measurement is likely to give the right answer.
\end{remark}

\section{Quantum model of computation}

Quantum model of computation has four stages:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item We start with an initial state $\ket{\psi}$
	\item Transform the state by performing unitary operations on the state to get a final state $\ket{\phi}$
	\item Measure the state $\ket{\phi}$ in a basis of choice
	\item Perform analyses on the measurement outcomes
\end{enumerate}

Hereafter, we use a model of computation that uses two-level systems.



\section{Quantum Bits}

\begin{definition}[Qubit]
	A \emph{qubit} is the quantum analogue of a classical bit. Its state is a unit vector
	\[
		\ket{\psi} = \alpha\ket{0} + \beta\ket{1}, \quad |\alpha|^2 + |\beta|^2 = 1,
	\]
	where $\alpha, \beta \in \CC$. When the basis of representation and the basis of measurement are the same, one can read of the probabilities of measuring a given basis state as the square of the modulus of the amplitude. In this case, for example, given we measure in the computational basis, Measurement yields outcome $0$ with probability $|\alpha|^2$
	and outcome $1$ with probability $|\beta|^2$.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Single qubits}
Every single-qubit state can be written in the Bloch sphere parametrisation:
\[
	\ket{\psi} = \cos\!\tfrac{\theta}{2}\,\ket{0} + e^{i\varphi}\sin\!\tfrac{\theta}{2}\,\ket{1},
\]
where $\theta \in [0,\pi]$ is the polar angle and $\varphi \in [0, 2\pi)$ is the azimuthal angle. There is also an overall global phase which is not mentioned here. As long as the phase is global it can be ignored. [Refer to appendix for the distinction between global and relative phases]

