\section{Universality of $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$}
\label{sec:hst-univ}

While single-qubit gates plus $\CNOT$ give exact universality over an infinite gate set, it
is desirable to have a \emph{finite} gate set that is universal in the approximation sense.
The set $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$---where $S = \Rz(\pi/2)$ is the phase gate and $T = \Rz(\pi/4)$
is the $\pi/8$ gate---is the standard such set.

\begin{definition}[Phase gate]
	The phase (or $S$) gate is
	\[
		S = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & i\end{pmatrix} = \Rz\!\left(\tfrac{\pi}{2}\right)\cdot e^{i\pi/4}.
	\]
	Note $S^2 = Z$ and $S^4 = I$.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Universality of $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$]
	\label{thm:hscnott-univ}
	The gate set $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$ is universal for quantum computation: any $n$-qubit
	unitary can be approximated to arbitrary precision $\varepsilon > 0$ using gates from this
	set, with the number of gates scaling as $O(\log^c(1/\varepsilon))$ per single-qubit gate
	(Solovay-Kitaev) .
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
	We show the set is universal in three stages.

	\textbf{Stage 1: $\{H, S\}$ generates a dense subgroup of $SU(2)$.}
	The Hadamard gate acts as $H\ket{0} = \ket{+}$, $H\ket{1} = \ket{-}$, corresponding to a
	$\pi$ rotation about the axis $(x+z)/\sqrt{2}$ on the Bloch sphere. The phase gate $S$
	gives a $\pi/2$ rotation about the $z$-axis. Since the rotation angle $\pi/2$ is not a
	rational multiple of $\pi$, repeated application of $H$ and $S$ generates rotations about
	non-parallel axes by incommensurable angles, producing a dense subgroup of $SU(2)$.\footnote{
		More precisely, $\{H, S\}$ alone is \emph{not} universal without $T$; it generates only the
		finite Clifford group on one qubit. The role of $T$ is to escape this finite group.}

	\textbf{Stage 2: Adding $T$ escapes the Clifford group.}
	The gate set $\{H, S\}$ generates only the single-qubit Clifford group, which is a finite
	group of 24 elements and is not dense in $SU(2)$. The $T$ gate has order 8 ($T^8 = I$), but
	the combination $HT$ is a rotation about an axis not aligned with any Clifford-group axis,
	and the product $HTHT$ introduces an angle incommensurable with $\pi/2$. Together $\{H, T\}$
	generate a dense subgroup of $SU(2)$, and hence $\{H, S, T\}$ is universal for single-qubit
	gates in the approximation sense. By the Solovay-Kitaev theorem, $O(\log^c(1/\varepsilon))$
	gates from $\{H, S, T\}$ suffice to approximate any single-qubit gate to error $\varepsilon$.

	\textbf{Stage 3: Adding $\CNOT$ gives multi-qubit universality.}
	By Theorem~\ref{thm:sq-cnot-univ}, single-qubit gates plus $\CNOT$ are sufficient for
	arbitrary multi-qubit unitaries. Since single-qubit gates can be approximated by $\{H, S, T\}$
	to any desired precision, and $\CNOT$ is already in the set, the full set $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$
	is universal for $n$-qubit computation.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
	The role of each gate in the set can be summarised as follows. $H$ creates superpositions
	and connects the $x$- and $z$-axes. $S$ provides a quarter-turn phase that, together with
	$H$, generates the Clifford group. $T$ is the ``non-Clifford'' gate that makes the group
	infinite and dense. $\CNOT$ is the entangling gate that promotes single-qubit universality
	to multi-qubit universality. No proper subset of $\{H, S, \CNOT, T\}$ is universal: removing
	$T$ leaves only the classically simulable Clifford group (Gottesman-Knill,
	\\Cref{ch:circuit-foundations}), removing $\CNOT$ restricts to product states, and removing
	$H$ or $S$ breaks the density argument in Stage~1.
\end{remark}
\section{Reversibility, Fanout, and the Clifford Group}

Probabilistic circuits are constructed via a coin-flipping gate. Non-unitary quantum gates
can be simulated by unitary gates given an ancilla register and permission to discard outputs.
Fanout and wire splitting are both permitted by linearity.

\begin{lemma}
	For any classical computation, there exists a quantum computation of comparable efficiency.
\end{lemma}

\begin{theorem}[Gottesman-Knill Theorem {\cite{gottesman1998}}]
	If a quantum algorithm uses only gates from the Clifford group
	$\{\CNOT, H, T, X, Y, Z\}$, it can be efficiently simulated by a classical probabilistic
	algorithm. Quantum algorithms with sufficiently little entanglement can also be efficiently
	simulated classically.
\end{theorem}

This establishes that entanglement is a necessary resource for quantum speedup beyond
classical probabilistic computation.
